\begin_layout Subsection
4-Momentum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the high velocities of particles in the accelerator , speical
 relativity must be applied when addressing the subject of decays and interactio
ns.
 Let us define the 4-momentum of a particle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{\mu}=(E,\overrightarrow{p})\label{4-momentum}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where E is the particle's energy and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{p}$
\end_inset

 is its spacial momentum.
 We can also define the invarient mass of the particle, which is the same
 in all frames of reference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{0}^{2}=E^{2}-\left\Vert \overrightarrow{p}\right\Vert ^{2}\label{Invarient Mass}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the rest mass of the particle, the invarient mass.
 Using the invarient mass through this equality is a strong tool when adressing
 decays, as demonstrated below.
 In conjunction with the invarient mass, another fundamental conservation
 is that of the 4-momentum in a certain frame of reference, which along
 with the invarient mass can yield info we desire about the particle (e.g
 its mass and energy).
 Suppose a particle decays into two particles whose momentums and masses
 are known 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1},\overrightarrow{p}_{1},m_{2},\overrightarrow{p}_{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1},\overrightarrow{p}_{1}$
\end_inset

 are the corresponding mass and momentum of the first particle and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2},\overrightarrow{p}_{2}$
\end_inset

are the corresponding mass and momentum of the second particle.
 Using the conservation of 4-momentum before and after the decay and the
 invarient mass in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Invarient Mass"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, one can derive the following relation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{0}^{2}=m_{1}^{2}+m_{2}^{2}+2\sqrt{m_{1}^{2}+\left\Vert \overrightarrow{p_{1}}\right\Vert }\sqrt{m_{2}^{2}+\left\Vert \overrightarrow{p_{2}}\right\Vert }-2\overrightarrow{p}_{1}\cdot\overrightarrow{p}_{2}\label{Decay}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{p}_{1}\cdot\overrightarrow{p}_{2}$
\end_inset

 denotes the dot product of the two momenta.
 
