 in it in several ways.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Photons' Energy Deposit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
1)The Photoelectric Effect:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A photon can deposit its entire energy by ionizing an electron from an atom
 and providing it with kinteic energy.
 Energy conservation must be maintained and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E_{\gamma}=h\nu=I_{B}+T_{e}\label{Photoelectric effect}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is the photons energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is its frequency, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{B}$
\end_inset

 is the energy required to free the electron from the atom and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{e}$
\end_inset

 is the kinetic energy of the now free electron[6] (Das Ferbel page 147).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
2) Compton Scattering:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can think of this process as the collision of a photon with frequency
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 with a free electron at rest, thus delivering some of its energy and momentum
 to the electron.
 Unlike the photoelectric effect, the photon does not deposit its entire
 energy.
 The energy deposited by the photon into the medium in this case can be
 derived 4-momentum conservation and mass invarience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
3) Pair Production:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a photon has sufficient energy, it can be absorbed into the medium
 and produce an electron-positron (the antiparticle of the electron) pair.
 This conversion can only occur by having the photon deliver some of its
 momentum , but very little energy to nearby nucleus, otherwise momentum-energy
 conservation is violated [7] (Das Ferbel page 149).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Electrons' Energy Deposit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
1) Ionization:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Electrons can ionize atoms in their path by interacting electromagnetically
 with the bound electrons, thus delivering some of their energy to the now
 free electrons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
2) Bremsstrahlung:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When electrons accelerate or deaccelerate as a result of electromagnetic
 interactions with the medium, they emit energy in the form of photons.
 This form of energy loss becomes dominant in higher energies [8] (Das Ferbel
 page 143).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a highly energetic photon or electron passes through the medium, it
 can create 'showers', these are avalanches of photons and electrons created
 by the original particle.
 Suppose that original particle is a photon, it can therefore ionize atoms
 via the photoelectric effect.
 The resulting free electrons can now ionize atoms themselves or emit photons
 via bremsstrahlung and thus a 'shower' is created, ending with the deposit
 of all the energy of the energetic particle in the medium.
\end_layout

